&lt;p&gt;Graphs are mathematical objects defined with a tuple &lt;code&gt;(V, E)&lt;/code&gt;, where V is a set of vertices and E are a set of edges connecting said vertices. For example:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class="err"&gt;$$G = (\{X, Y, Z\}, \{(X, Y), (Y, Z)\})$$&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;is a graph. Graphs as their name suggest are "graphical" representations of things that have "relationships" with other things. The graphical aspect is nice because we can easily draw the graph in question as such.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="math"&gt;\(&lt;div class="math"&gt;\begin{tikzpicture}\node (v0) at (-2.20,1.52) {A};
\node (v1) at (1.40,-1.62) {D};
\node (v2) at (-0.512,-0.127) {E};
\draw [-&amp;gt;] (v0) edge (v2);
\draw [-&amp;gt;,&amp;lt;-] (v1) edge (v2);\end{tikzpicture}&lt;/div&gt;\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
